<div id="review_778561329" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/778561329" />
    <a title="Matthew Hunter" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3040804-matthew-hunter"><img alt="Matthew Hunter" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1495642903p2/3040804.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/778561329?book_show_action=true">Dec 01, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matthew Hunter" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matthew Hunter" href="/user/show/3040804-matthew-hunter">Matthew Hunter</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3040804-matthew-hunter?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3040804-matthew-hunter?shelf=lebanese-literature">lebanese-literature</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer778561329" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9023514547745556950">Good God <i>Leo Africanus</i> is a great book! It&apos;s epic in scope, reminding me a bit of <i>Forrest Gump</i> in the way that Hasan/Leo keeps popping up during major historical events. His family runs into Christopher Columbus before the explorer heads to the New World. He&apos;s present in Cairo as the armies of the Grand Turk overwhelm the city. He&apos;s holed up in Castel San Angelo as hordes friendly to Emperor Charles sack the &quot;Eternal City&quot;. He watches from a hilltop the complete destruction of Timbuktu by fire. </span>
  <span id="freeText9023514547745556950" style="display:none">Good God <i>Leo Africanus</i> is a great book! It's epic in scope, reminding me a bit of <i>Forrest Gump</i> in the way that Hasan/Leo keeps popping up during major historical events. His family runs into Christopher Columbus before the explorer heads to the New World. He's present in Cairo as the armies of the Grand Turk overwhelm the city. He's holed up in Castel San Angelo as hordes friendly to Emperor Charles sack the "Eternal City". He watches from a hilltop the complete destruction of Timbuktu by fire. His family flees Granada after it falls to the Castilian Christians of Ferdinand and Isabella - aka Columbus's sugar daddies.<br /><br />Imagine being held in high regard by Popes, emperors, and Shaikhs, one day playing diplomat for Sultans and hearing the Muezzin's call to prayer, the next day being baptized by Pope Leo X, hanging out with the Medicis, and having Rafael ask to paint you. That's the ecclectic life of our Hasan/Leo.<br /><br />I'm biased toward books that give me the opportunity to think about important matters in creative ways. Maalouf didn't disalpoint me. Here's one example out of many:<blockquote><br />"If death was not inevitable, man would have wasted his whole life attempting to avoid it. He would have risked nothing, attempted nothing, undertaken nothing, invented nothing, built nothing. Life would have been a perpetual convalescence. Yes my brothers, let us thank God for having made us this gift of death, so that life is to have meaning; of night, that day is to have meaning; silence, that speech is to have meaning; illness, that health is to have meaning; war, that peace is to have meaning. Let us give thanks to Him for having given us weariness and pain, so that rest and joy are to have meaning. Let us give thanks to Him, Whose wisdom is infinite."</blockquote><br />Outside of the diversity of teachings about the significance of Christ's crucifixion and resurrection, I've seldom encountered the idea of death as gift. Great! Now I have multiple reasons to stop obsessing about my own mortality! :)<br /><br />It's not only the material between the covers that makes <i>Leo Africanus</i> great. The cover includes a detail from Peeter Pauwel Rubens' <i>Mulay Ahmad</i>. It's beautiful. Check out the way Rubens depicts light reflecting in his subject's eyes, on the tip of his nose, and his lips. The guy had skill! One of my favorite covers ever.<br /><br />An easy 5 stars for me. Enjoy!</span>
  <a data-text-id="9023514547745556950" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

