<div id="review_1267333832" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1267333832" />
    <a title="Ingy Higazy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16275841-ingy-higazy"><img alt="Ingy Higazy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1388756118p2/16275841.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1267333832?book_show_action=true">Apr 29, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ingy Higazy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ingy Higazy" href="/user/show/16275841-ingy-higazy">Ingy Higazy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1267333832" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer756366137447574573">I am spellbound. And I blame myself for the times when I used to carry this book around in my backpack last summer for days without laying hands on it. I began reading the book again -from the very first chapter- a few ago. I was naturally drawn to it (and actually purchased it) because of the first book, &quot;The Book of Granada.&quot; Maalouf had indeed taken me on a journey through many &quot;accursed cities,&quot; Granada and elsewhere, yes. But most importantly, it was his account of Hasan&apos;s/Leo&apos;s reflections</span>
  <span id="freeText756366137447574573" style="display:none">I am spellbound. And I blame myself for the times when I used to carry this book around in my backpack last summer for days without laying hands on it. I began reading the book again -from the very first chapter- a few ago. I was naturally drawn to it (and actually purchased it) because of the first book, "The Book of Granada." Maalouf had indeed taken me on a journey through many "accursed cities," Granada and elsewhere, yes. But most importantly, it was his account of Hasan's/Leo's reflections on, feelings, and judgements about 'home and exile' that was particularly captivating, and that appealed to me a great deal.<br /><br />I am already writing about the book here, a few hours after laying it to rest. Yet, they are words that sound more like a frenzied text to a friend than a book review. I don't think that matters much now. Seriously though, read the book if you're a little into medieval history, but also in the mood for an eloquent reflection on the meaning of home and of exile. You will undoubtedly be led to reflect yourself on, and to question, the inevitability or futility of social/cultural assimilation in our 'contemporary' world. </span>
  <a data-text-id="756366137447574573" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


