    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3413877764" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3413877764" />
    <a title="MadZiddi" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4571120-madziddi"><img alt="MadZiddi" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1570091731p2/4571120.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3413877764?book_show_action=true">Jul 24, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="MadZiddi" class="user" itemprop="url" name="MadZiddi" href="/user/show/4571120-madziddi">MadZiddi</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3413877764" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10667459575934954571">The fact that Amin Malouf&apos;s historic fiction reads like a dream ( and I have just read the heart-rending nightmare of the fall of Granada, Rome, and Cairo through eyes of a resident), might lead one to construe that historical fiction is easy to write. However, this seems very unlikely given the fact, that apart from Qazi Abdul Sattar and the Malouf, I have not come across realistic modern historic fiction. Most authors like Naseem Hijazi pander to the revisionist and romanticized historical ins</span>
  <span id="freeText10667459575934954571" style="display:none">The fact that Amin Malouf's historic fiction reads like a dream ( and I have just read the heart-rending nightmare of the fall of Granada, Rome, and Cairo through eyes of a resident), might lead one to construe that historical fiction is easy to write. However, this seems very unlikely given the fact, that apart from Qazi Abdul Sattar and the Malouf, I have not come across realistic modern historic fiction. Most authors like Naseem Hijazi pander to the revisionist and romanticized historical instincts of the masses. Not that Malouf does not take romantic liberties, but he gives a humanistic account of the European and Afro-Arabic societies on the eve of reformation and renaissance. One of the secrets of Malouf's success as a master of modern historical fiction is that instead of writing fictionalized biographies of Kings and conquerors, he has sought to build a kaleidoscope of events around the life of Middle East thinkers and adventurers like Khayyam, Mani and in this case, Hassan Al Wazzan who left an impression not only their birthplace but rather Modern Europe. The fact that this entailed them being free thinkers ahead of their times in anachronistic societies meant they were easy targets for the dogmatic establishment of the day. Such idealistic men are easy to admire and Malouf seems to find it easy to often interweave several amorous affairs, no doubt adding masala which is usually popular with readers. However, it cannot be concluded that Malouf is a formula author. Far from it, in this particular, this novel is unique in the sense that it is of an adventurer, moving from Granada, to Fez, to Cairo, Timbuktu and Rome and finally to Constantinople and making and losing fortunes in the process. painting unique portraits of the Middle East in turmoil as Christian Iberians and Turk Ottomans strangle the Arab hold in North Africa and the Catholic church is threatened by Absolute Kingship and reformation in Europe. As Hassan finds himself Castilians inquisitors in Granada, to easy-going religion in Timbuktu to conversion to Christianity in Rome, Hasan finds himself in the centre of debate between religions and keeping humanism alive in the age of zealotry. Perhaps these debates are still relevant today as religion and modernism feel iself threatened in turn by each other in Eastern and Western societies respectively.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10667459575934954571" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

