<div id="review_2785360559" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2785360559" />
    <a title="Alison" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7701175-alison"><img alt="Alison" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1562315654p2/7701175.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2785360559?book_show_action=true">Jun 09, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alison" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alison" href="/user/show/7701175-alison">Alison</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/19289413-leo-africanus">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7701175-alison?shelf=2019challenge">2019challenge</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7701175-alison?shelf=biography">biography</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7701175-alison?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2785360559" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7768981071854295943">In this gripping adventure tale, Maalouf uses the historical Hasan ibn Muhammad al-Wazzan, as a narrative structure to explore turn-of-the-sixteenth century North Africa and Spain. Maalouf brings to life a world of grand cities, lives punctuated by the call to prayer, intriguing factions, lengthy and tedious merchant caravans, and the complex world of loving polygamous households.<br/>Al-Wazzan provides a great central figure. Too much about him is unknown to make an accurate biography, but enough is</span>
  <span id="freeText7768981071854295943" style="display:none">In this gripping adventure tale, Maalouf uses the historical Hasan ibn Muhammad al-Wazzan, as a narrative structure to explore turn-of-the-sixteenth century North Africa and Spain. Maalouf brings to life a world of grand cities, lives punctuated by the call to prayer, intriguing factions, lengthy and tedious merchant caravans, and the complex world of loving polygamous households.<br />Al-Wazzan provides a great central figure. Too much about him is unknown to make an accurate biography, but enough is known to ensure that an extraordinary story is plausible, if not always likely. Maalouf uses this to create a man in love with travel, endlessly curious, who has a knack of stumbling into some of the greatest events of his time. The novel hence explores not only the Muslim world of the time, but the feeling of retreat, as the Christian expansion moves forward. Intra-Christian and intra-Muslim divisions also abound, and Maalouf draws out the complex world of shifting alliances as city states give way to vast empires, and a way of life continues to evolve.<br />The book largely works because Hasan feels so realised. You feel the tension between his love of travel and restlessness and his deep connections to family and the women in it in particular. He exists as both an insider, connected to communities and values, and an outsider, with multiple loyalties, in all the locales he visits.<br />The book's strengths are hence worldbuilding, suspense, travelogue and good characters. I wouldn't say it is especially profound, and the tone is less smooth in translation than I suspect in the original French, but I found it fun and enlightening, and such a pleasure to spend time in this spacetime place, which gets rare treatment in the stuffed historical fiction genre.<br /><br />2019 Reading Challenge #33. A book with a zodiac sign or astrology term in title</span>
  <a data-text-id="7768981071854295943" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


