              <span id="reviewTextContainer2200179727" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9668992397634229897">Leo Africanus is an epic travel journey seen from the eyes of our protagonist Hasan who assumes many identities over 40 years of time period depicted in the book. The journey starts in Al Andalus before the fall of Granada and winds its way through Fez, Timbuktu, Cairo, Constantinople, Mecca, and Rome amongst other cities. The story of these cities at that time is spoken very eloquently through Hasan (and Leo) but since the protagonist has to be in many great cities and has to take many epic jou</span>
  <span id="freeText9668992397634229897" style="display:none">Leo Africanus is an epic travel journey seen from the eyes of our protagonist Hasan who assumes many identities over 40 years of time period depicted in the book. The journey starts in Al Andalus before the fall of Granada and winds its way through Fez, Timbuktu, Cairo, Constantinople, Mecca, and Rome amongst other cities. The story of these cities at that time is spoken very eloquently through Hasan (and Leo) but since the protagonist has to be in many great cities and has to take many epic journeys in 40 years the book seems disjointed as all of it is crammed in just 350 pages. Also there is hardly any time for character development.<br /><br />At the same time the book succeeds in evoking nostalgia for that era and specially enjoyed the books of Granada &amp; Fez as they are two of my favorite cities in the world.<br /></span>
